Satellite tag derived movements of Aus SRW at Kerguelen

Virginia Andrews-Goff

14 February, 2024, 13:11

This RMarkdown file delves into the satellite tag derived SRW movements from Kate Sprogis’ deployments on Aus SRW. As it’s likely that the full tracks will be used in other projects, I have restricted the detailed work to the area adjacent to Kerguelen.

What data was collected for these three whales that use the Kerguelen region?
Whale 235409 setup file indicates that all histograms were disabled.
Whale 235410 setup file indicates that all histograms were disabled.
Whale 235414 - no set up file. Dipping into the folder, there is min/max depth, histograms, dive shape.
Min/max depth = min and max depths per 6 hour summary window.
Behaviour - Each row of this spreadsheet represents one type of behavior reported by the instrument.
Histograms - need tag program to decode and use.
Series - Subsampled archive data = less detailed dive profiles essentially.

Proposed workflow: 1) Process all Argos locations within the ssm/move persistence framework; 2) Generate locations for the relevant dive data files; 3) Subset to Kerguelen region and 4) Charactertise horizontal and vertical behaviour in the area.

Also need an understanding of appropriate dive definition - what was programmed into the tags (> 10m and > 1 min, for example)?

1- ARGOS TRACKS

1.1 - Cleaning raw tracks

Just a few things to modify on the raw tracks. Argos Kalman Filter (or Kalman Smoother) data should have 8 columns in the following order: id, date, lc, lon, lat. Where date can be a POSIX object or text string in YYYY-MM-DD HH:MM:SS format. lc (location class) can include the following values: 3, 2, 1, 0, A, B, Z. Class Z values are assumed to have the same error variances as class B. Then smaj, smin, eor that contain Argos error ellipse variables (in m for smaj, smin and deg for eor).

# remove useless columns and rename columns with shorter names
raw_argos_df_WA <- raw_argos_df_WA[c("Ptt", "Date", "Quality", "Longitude", "Latitude", "Error.Semi.major.axis", "Error.Semi.minor.axis", "Error.Ellipse.orientation")]
names(raw_argos_df_WA) <- c("id", "date", "lc", "lon", "lat", "smaj", "smin", "eor")

#Format the date - should be 'yyyy-mm-dd hh:mm:ss"
raw_argos_df_WA$date <- as.POSIXct(raw_argos_df_WA$date, format = "%H:%M:%S %d-%b-%Y", tz="GMT")

# Order the data by id and date

# Remove data generated before tag deployment (testing for example)

2- CLEANING UP THE ARGOS TRACKS

pre_dup <- nrow(raw_argos_df_WA) # to get the current number of data points

# create dummy variable
raw_argos_df_WA$index <- c(1:nrow(raw_argos_df_WA))

# run each tag in a loop check to check for duplicates
# if there is a time duplicate, select the best quality position or simply the first position
raw_argos_df_WA <- ddply(raw_argos_df_WA, ~id, function(d){
  toremove <- c()
  for (i in c(2:nrow(d))) {
    if (d$date[i] == d$date[i-1]) {
      dd <- d[(i-1):i,]
      r <- dd[dd$lc == ave(dd$lc, FUN = min), "index"] # find the lowest quality
      toremove <- c(toremove, r[1]) #select first element of r in case both locations have the same lq
    }
  }
  if (length(toremove) > 0){d <- d[!(d$index %in% toremove), ]}
  return(d)
})
# remove dummy variable
raw_argos_df_WA$index <- NULL

I tend to split tracks with data gaps > 24h. This code is easily adapted to whatever split looks sensible. Below I have chosen 48 hours.

trackseg_argos_df_WA <- ddply(time_diff_hours_df_WA, ~id, function(d){
ind <- which(d$time_diff_hours > 48) #48 = 48 hours

d$track_seg <- cumsum(d$mark)
  return(d)
})

To choose a time step, for the time being I’ll be informed by the “text book approach.” First of all the mean time diff is:

mean(mts$seg_diff_hours) #2.85
## [1] 2.845591

This indicates 1 Argos location every ~3 hours. As a general rule of thumb, generating one ssm location for 3 Argos locations is a good approach, though often somewhat conservative. It’s a start. So, if I need to time step later, I’ll run with a 6h, 9h and 12h model to compare. Best to start with no time step unless future analyses require it.

4- THE STATE SPACE MODEL AND MOVE PERSISTENCE MODEL
aniMotum provides a move persistence model in state-space form to allow simultaneous estimation of move persistence and location states, and this is invoked via fit_ssm() by specifying model = “mp”. Apparently, this model can only be fit to individuals separately but when your run the code on tracks together, it appears to work.

We will generate a SSM location estimate at each oberved location estimate time. The SSM location estimate accounts for Argos location error and has an associated value of move persistence (continuous-valued behavioural index). Move persistence estimates the time-varying autocorrelation in speed and directionality along an animal’s track. The resulting move persistence (γ) value at each location provides an index of behaviour (between 0-1). Move persistence values approaching 1 indicate faster, straighter movements associated with transit behaviour, while move persistence values approaching 0 indicate slower, more tortuous movements termed ‘area restricted search’ (assumed to be foraging/resting/breeding behaviour).

to_model_WA <- trackseg_argos_df_WA[,c("track_id", "date", "lc", "lon", "lat", "smaj", "smin", "eor")]
colnames(to_model_WA)[1] <- "id"

fit_ksrw <- fit_ssm(to_model_WA, vmax=10, model = "mp", time.step=NA, control = ssm_control(verbose = 0)) #worked

These plots demonstrate the uncertainty associated with the move persistence parameter and look pretty standard for this kind of data.

It would be worth trying to assess how confident we are in the derived/interpolated dive locations. Just to recap, the ssm/mpm is built using the Argos location data - a fairly dense data set when you compare it to the dive data sets. The dive data sets are not supplied with associated locations, only a timestamp. So we give the timestamp within the ssm/mpm process to derive locations. By plotting up the ssm locations and the dive locations against time, perhaps we can get a better idea of how well the derived dive locations fit in with the state space model locations estimates (from the Argos location data). Below I map the state space model assigned dive locations colour coded by max dive depth, then date, for an idea of what happened when. You can see that this data is much more sparse than the Argos data - keep in mind that it is subsampled dive profile data.

dive_lon <- ggplot(series_WA[series_WA$in_area=="yes",], aes(gmt, dive_lon)) + geom_point(col="blue")

TO DISCUSS: I don’t trust the way the move persistence model has assigned locations to the dives. We can do this analysis without locations for the dives, simply present dive behaviour. Or we can use another approach - CRAWL, for example, to assing dive locations. We would then probably need to ditch behavioral mode. Or we use the behavioural mode to discuss horizontal movements but rely entirely on CRAWL (assuming it does a better job) to discuss dive locations.

Here, I take a look at max dive depth relative to the bathymetric depth, acknowledging that there is some degree of uncertainty around the estimated dive locations and that’s with the assumption that the ssm/mpm has assigned these well, which I’m not certain of.

coordinates(series_WA) <- c("dive_lon", "dive_lat")

6- DIVING BEHAVIOUR - DIVE SHAPES
This dataset assigns a start and end time to a dive, assigns a dive shape according to bottom time and also provides depth and duration details.

start <- ymd_hms("2023-01-20 02:47:39", tz="GMT")
end <- ymd_hms("2023-02-08 02:57:11", tz="GMT")

behav_WA$Start <- as.POSIXct(behav_WA$Start, format = "%H:%M:%S %d-%b-%Y", tz="GMT")
behav_WA$End <- as.POSIXct(behav_WA$End, format = "%H:%M:%S %d-%b-%Y", tz="GMT")

behav_WA$in_area <- "no"
behav_WA$in_area[behav_WA$Start >= start & behav_WA$End <= end] <- "yes"

### Assign dive shape location using the state space model
behav_WA$seg_id <- "235414_0"
behav_WA$seg_id[as.Date(behav_WA$End) >= locs_235414$date[locs_235414$id=="235414_1"][1]] <- "235414_1"
## Warning in check_tzones(e1, e2): 'tzone' attributes are inconsistent
#prediction times must be specified as a data.frame with id and POSIXt dates
pred_gmt_behav <- behav_WA[behav_WA$What=="Dive",]
pred_gmt_behav <- pred_gmt_behav[,c("Start", "seg_id")]
colnames(pred_gmt_behav) <- c("date", "id")

mp_behav <- fit_ssm(locs_235414, vmax=10, model='crw', time.step=pred_gmt_behav, map = list(psi = factor(NA)), control = ssm_control(verbose = 0))
#ggsave(map(mp_behav, what="predicted"), file = paste(file.path(here::here('Outputs')), "/dive_shape_locations_235414.jpeg", sep=""), dpi = 300, width = 14, height = 8, bg="white")
